impersonate or kill. During the night, you should inspect players whose identities are uncertain (there is no need to check players who are highly suspected of being werewolves).\nWhen speaking during the day, your goal is to convince others that you are the real Seer. You must gather trust and\nshare your findings without exposing yourself too early. Even though revealing your identity might put you in danger,\na Seer trusted by both the Witch and the Guard can survive for at least three rounds if everyone acts accordingly.\nA good Seer will coordinate with the Witch and the Guard to divide responsibilities. For example, on the first night, the Guard protects the Seer, and the Witch doesn't use the antidote. On the second night, the Witch saves the Seer, and the Guard protects someone else.\n\n\nWitch Role Introduction:\nYou are the Witch. Each night, you will be told who has been attacked, and you must decide whether to use your antidote\nto save them or use your poison to eliminate another player. You only have one poison and one antidote, so use them wisely.\nDuring the daytime discussions, if the night ends without a death, you can reveal that you used your antidote to save someone, which may earn others' trust.\nTypically, you should use the antidote to save key players like the Seer, the Guard, or yourself, while the poison is best used to eliminate werewolves at night.\nHowever, be cautious: sometimes the werewolves will deliberately attack one of their own (self-knife strategy) to trick you into wasting the antidote, thereby boosting their credibility.\n\n\nGuard Role Introduction:\nYou are the Guard. Each night, you can choose one player to protect from being killed by the werewolves. You cannot protect\nthe same player two nights in a row. Your role is critical in keeping important players like the Seer or the Witch alive.\nYou are in a constant mental battle with the werewolves, trying to predict who they will target. It might not always be the Seer, as the werewolves might expect you to protect them and kill someone else. In general, you should avoid revealing your identity unless absolutely necessary.\n\n\n\n\nYou are Antionette, your role in this game is witch.\nWerewolf game starting. Initializing day-night cycle.\nSYSTEM: Starting day-night cycle for Day 1\nSYSTEM: Night 1 begins. Werewolves and special roles take actions.\nGuard has chosen to protect a player.\nWerewolves have chosen their target.\nSeer has checked a player's identity.\nWitch used poison on Devin.\nWitch has made her decision on potion use.\nSYSTEM: Day 1 begins. Players discuss and vote on potential suspects.\nNo candidates decided to run for sheriff. No sheriff in this game anymore.\nPlayers deceased during the night: Kelly, Devin\nLast words from Kelly: Fellow villagers, I am sorry to be eliminated so early, but I must share my suspicions with you. I believe Devin and Amanda are the werewolves. Devin's elimination with me on the first night is suspicious, as werewolves often target each other to mislead the group. Amanda's behavior has been inconsistent, and she seemed overly eager to protect Devin, which is unusual for a villager. Be cautious and gather more evidence before making accusations. Trust Elizabeth and Susan, and verify information before acting. Good luck to you all.\nPlayer Devin has been eliminated from the game.\nPlayer Kelly has been eliminated from the game.\nAmanda's speech: Thank you for letting me speak. I want to address Kelly's last words. While I understand her suspicions, I believe we need to be cautious and gather more evidence before making accusations. I deny being a werewolf and can explain my actions last night. I protected Devin because I believed he was in danger, and I wanted to ensure his safety. I also want to support Elizabeth and Susan, as Kelly suggested. Their behavior has not been suspicious, and I trust their judgment. Let's work together to gather more information and make informed decisions.\nAnti